-- feedback: よくやったよ！

Your pacing/rhythm is different from the example.
In きがします, you raise your intonation in the end and in the example, the last syllable has a more subtle intonation that falls in the end.

In シャドーイングですか, your か is a bit longer than the example's.

Keep practicing shadowing and recording yourself, it's a good way to improve pacing and intonation.

Cheers!

Assessment #2352344
-- 発音の良さ / Fluency of Pronunciation: まあ良い　Fair (2)
-- feedback: The pronunciation is good, especially the tones. However, there are a few issues.

The letter ず in 上手 (じょうず) should be pronounced as "zu", like pronouncing an "s" and forcing voice from your throat, not like "tsu". Also, the first dialog is declarative, so I guess the word します at the end should end in a low pitch, not a high one. On the other hand, the second dialog should end in a low pitch and pronounced slower to evoke a feeling of curiosity. The marker か at the end should be modulated (I don't really know how to modulate :( ) and pronounced high and low at the end in one go.

「ノートに」のアクセントが違っていました。「低低高低」→「高低低低」です。

Assessment Scores:
Assessment #2281868
-- 発音の良さ / Fluency of Pronunciation: 良い　Good (2)
-- feedback: Overall, I think it's good. Just take care with the intonation in the last part of the speech, "かさもってな～い". Remember the lesson saying that sentence intonation in Japanese is rather smooth? I felt that your recording was bit "jumpy", with many rise and falls especially on "ない". 

Don't know exactly how to put in words, but as a bit of advice on "うわあ", it felt to me like you slowly rise the pitch to reach the "top" on the last bit of "あ", when it should swiftly reach the top before, on "わ". The rest is nice in my opinion. Congrats and keep up the good work!
Assessment #2263190
-- 発音の良さ / Fluency of Pronunciation: まあ良い　Fair (2)
-- feedback: The intonation stands out as being very off, particularly towards the end, when you said 持ってない. That kind of wobbly (for lack of a better word) intonation doesn't really show up in Japanese in the same way that it does every now and then in English. 

In the first sentence, pay attention to the timing with which each syllable is pronounced. You've pronounced 降って and きた with more or less the same timing, but they need to be distinct, the former lasting 3 beats and the latter lasting 2.

The うわ in the second sentence isn't a gradual transition from う to あ. Make sure you enunciate both sounds, the う and the わ distinctly. 
Assessment #2263161
-- 発音の良さ / Fluency of Pronunciation: まあ良い　Fair (2)
-- feedback: Your 持ってない　sounds "funny" at the end because of that sudden increase in volume (really not sure if "volume" is the appropiate term)
Assessment #2263107
-- 発音の良さ / Fluency of Pronunciation: まあ良い　Fair (2)
-- feedback: For the second sentence, the intonation should be flat as heard in the sample, rather than rising.  Be careful with pitch!

"かんじカードも" sounded like "かんじカードーも".

-- 発音の良さ / Fluency of Pronunciation: まあ良い　Fair (2)
-- feedback: This was quite good! I have two points of advice:
1. Focus on your intonation a little more. It's a little off. Not bad, though, as far as I can tell.
2. The timing of syllables needs to be more refined. 持って and 降って don't have the same timing as きた and 傘. The first two have the duration of three syllables: も・っ・て, ふ・っ・て. The last two, on the other hand, have only two: き・た, か・さ. As such, there needs to be a distinction made between the timing of the first group and the timing of the second group.

Good job otherwise!

「にほんごを」のアクセントが違っていました。「低高高低低」→「低高高高高」です。声の高さに気をつけましょう。
The accent for "にほんごを" was not correct. It sounded like “LHHLL”. The correct accent is “LHHHH”. Be careful of pitch.

「かんじカードも」のアクセントが違っていました。「高高低高高高高」→「低高高高低低低」です。
The accent for "かんじカードも" was not correct. It sounded like “HHLHHHH”. The correct accent is “LHHHLLL”.

Takako Toda (Waseda University)
Assessment Scores:
Assessment #2264659
-- 発音の良さ / Fluency of Pronunciation: まあ良い　Fair (2)
-- feedback: はっきりと発音していて、とても聞きやすかったです。伝わる発音で、とても良かったです。
Your pronunciation was clear and easy to listen to. It was very good pronunciation that communicated your intention.

「おはようございます」が「おはよございます」に聞こえました。声の長さに気をつけましょう。
"おはようございます" sounded like "おはよございます". Be careful of the long vowel sound.

「どうやって」のアクセントが違っていました。「低低高低低」に聞こえましたが、「低高高高高」が正解です。声の高さに気をつけましょう。
The accent for "どうやって" was not correct. It sounded like "LLHLL", but the correct accent is "LHHHH". Be careful of pitch.

「ほんとうに」が「ほんどに」に聞こえました。
"ほんとうに" sounded like "ほんどに".

「かーども」のアクセントが違っていました。「高低低高」に聞こえましたが、「高低低低」が正解です。声の高さに気をつけましょう。
The accent for "かーども" was not correct. It sounded like "HLLH", but the correct accent is "HLLH". Be careful of pitch.

これからも、発音練習をがんばってください！
Keep trying your best to practice your pronunciation!
大熊伊宗

-- 発音の良さ / Fluency of Pronunciation: まあ良い　Fair (2)
-- feedback: In American style English, vowels sound fairly strong. However, in Japanese, they seem to be softer. For example, the "あ" is pronounced more like "ahh,'' where the mouth opens more and is less nasal. However, if you say the "a" as in the word "cat, " you should be able to hear a very slight difference in the pronunciation.
Also, don't forget that in "ふって" the small "っ" requires a pause in the word. Its almost closing your lips in the middle of the sound to stop it, but then you continue. Just like how you pronounced "もって" correctly in the following line.

はっきりと発音していて、とても聞きやすかったです。
Your pronunciation was clear and easy to listen to.
最初の「おはようございます」のアクセントが違っていました。
「低高高低低低低低低」→「低高高高高高高高低」です。
The accent for the initial "おはようございます" was not correct.
It sounded like “LHHLLLLLL”. The correct accent is “LHHHHHHHL”.
「ノート」のアクセントが違っていました。「低低低」→「高低低」です。
The accent for "ノート" was not correct.
It sounded like “LLL”. The correct accent is “HLL”.
声の高さに気をつけましょう。
Be careful of pitch.
これからも、発音練習をがんばってください！
Keep trying your best to practice your pronunciation!

So you'd just listen to the original carefully, and then try to pronounce 東京オリンピック over and over about 20-30 times to get it as similar to the original as possible.   
Also, the "ou"-s in "Toukyou/とうきょう" are long, so try to stretch them out a bit more.
 The whole high/low thing is confusing for advanced students, too, so don't worry too much about not being perfect on the first try. :D

Good luck!

The second phrase, "arigatou gozaimasu", seemed to perhaps be pronounced as two words rather than one - notably, the pitch falls at the end of "arigatou" and begins to rise again towards the beginning of "gozaimasu". -- scorer_id: 9597d232828d261383870006e167ec10
-- overall_feedback: 発音の高低アクセントが良かったと思います。
「ありがとう」の「り」はちょっと日本語の滑らかな「り」より粗かったですが、それに関わらず内容が伝わりました。「ら、り、る、れ、ろ」についての発音は個人的にも難しいです。舌の居場所と使用についての問題ですから、それに集中すればきっと発音がもっときれいに聞こえるでしょう。:)

I think the accent (high/low) was good.
The "ri" in "arigatou" was a bit rougher in comparison to the soft Japanese version, but the content was, of course, completely understandable.
The "ra, ri, ru, re, ro" was personally difficult for me, too, so I suggest you work on the position and movement of your tongue and try a lot of "ra-ri-ru-re-ro" exercises. Good luck! :)
